WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.776 --> 00:00:05.026
(uptempo techno music)

00:00:27.150 --> 00:00:29.510
- Welcome to a Conversation With History.

00:00:29.510 --> 00:00:30.648
I'm Harry Kreisler of

00:00:30.648 --> 00:00:32.694
the Institute of International Studies.

00:00:32.694 --> 00:00:35.020
Our guest today is John Yoo,

00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:36.820
who is Professor of Law

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:39.280
at the University of California Berkeley,

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:40.900
Boalt School of Law.

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:44.263
He's the author of The
Powers of War and Peace,

00:00:44.263 --> 00:00:48.233
and War By Other Means:
An Insider's Account

00:00:48.233 --> 00:00:50.647
of the War on Terror.

00:00:50.647 --> 00:00:53.170
John, welcome to the program.

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:54.210
- Thanks for having me.

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:55.875
- Where were you born and raised?

00:00:55.875 --> 00:00:58.329
- I was born in Seoul, South Korea,

00:00:58.329 --> 00:01:01.810
and was raised in the Philadelphia area.

00:01:01.810 --> 00:01:04.580
So, I came over here
from the United States,

00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:07.448
to the United States when
I was three months old.

00:01:07.448 --> 00:01:10.069
Initially grew up in southern New Jersey

00:01:10.069 --> 00:01:13.754
then grew up ultimately in
the Philadelphia suburbs.

00:01:13.754 --> 00:01:16.685
- And looking back, how
do you think your parents

00:01:16.685 --> 00:01:19.520
shaped your thinking about the world?

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:22.223
- Well, there's a lot of different ways.

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:27.111
One, they were immigrants
from another country.

00:01:27.111 --> 00:01:30.448
I think that was very important to me,

00:01:30.448 --> 00:01:34.480
the idea that you would leave the country

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:36.040
you grew up in and went to school in,

00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:38.077
and go to an entirely different country,

00:01:38.077 --> 00:01:41.707
something I think is very hard
for Americans to understand,

00:01:41.707 --> 00:01:43.350
there's not a lot of immigration

00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:45.290
from America to other countries,

00:01:45.290 --> 00:01:48.838
so I think that's one
thing is that how strong

00:01:48.838 --> 00:01:52.080
the pull of the United States is

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:53.636
on people in other countries.

00:01:53.636 --> 00:01:55.820
Second thing is, you know,

00:01:55.820 --> 00:01:58.950
I think they fled military
dictatorship, at the time.

00:01:58.950 --> 00:02:02.780
South Korea in the 1960s and in the 1970s

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:04.274
was a military dictatorship.

00:02:04.274 --> 00:02:07.140
And so, there's a big contrast I think,

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:09.223
between there and the kind of

00:02:09.223 --> 00:02:12.837
political, and economic, and
social freedoms one has here.

00:02:12.837 --> 00:02:15.430
And the third one, obviously, Korea is

00:02:15.430 --> 00:02:18.266
a divided country to this day,

00:02:18.266 --> 00:02:21.137
and there's this famous shot from space

00:02:21.137 --> 00:02:23.433
of the Korea peninsula at night.

00:02:23.433 --> 00:02:26.970
And you can see the northern
half is completely black.

00:02:26.970 --> 00:02:30.040
And the southern half is full of light,

00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:32.000
as is the Western world.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.240
And so, one of the last
thing I got from my parents,

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:39.837
I think, was their deep
suspicion of communism,

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:42.703
and the Soviet Union,

00:02:43.763 --> 00:02:46.160
And because of that, more
sympathy, and you know,

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:48.690
when I got older in the
American political system,

00:02:48.690 --> 00:02:51.141
of people who did not
think that the communists

00:02:51.141 --> 00:02:54.460
were gonna win or were a
legitimate political system.

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:57.580
And that fighting expansion
of the Soviet Union

00:02:57.580 --> 00:02:59.267
was a good thing.
- Mm-hmm.

00:02:59.267 --> 00:03:02.160
Was there a discussion
of politics, the law,

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:04.215
around the dinner table?

00:03:04.215 --> 00:03:06.013
- No, I'm sorry, I don't have

00:03:06.013 --> 00:03:08.461
one of those great
stories growing up where

00:03:08.461 --> 00:03:12.279
my parents are cross-examining the kids

00:03:12.279 --> 00:03:14.510
about politics and who to vote for.

00:03:14.510 --> 00:03:18.740
In fact, both, all I know about
my parents' political views

00:03:18.740 --> 00:03:20.900
is that one of them is a Republican

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:22.700
and one of them is a Democrat

00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:24.340
but I'm not sure which one is which,

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:26.190
and they've never told me, so

00:03:26.190 --> 00:03:27.910
we didn't talk a lot about,

00:03:27.910 --> 00:03:31.850
partisan or party politics
at the table at all.

00:03:31.850 --> 00:03:34.252
You know, so I can't,

00:03:34.252 --> 00:03:37.470
I can't say that my views were shaped

00:03:37.470 --> 00:03:40.190
at the dinner table, or
my skills as a lawyer

00:03:40.190 --> 00:03:42.352
was shaped from arguing
with my parents and sibling

00:03:42.352 --> 00:03:44.770
about politics and law.

00:03:44.770 --> 00:03:46.590
- Where did you do your undergraduate work

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:47.810
and then your law degree?

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:51.610
- I went to Harvard College
and I majored in history,

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:54.033
American diplomatic history in particular.

00:03:55.410 --> 00:03:57.050
I wrote my undergraduate thesis

00:03:57.050 --> 00:04:00.740
about efforts to cooperate in
the sharing of nuclear weapons

00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:03.030
between the United States and
Western Europe in the 1960s.

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:06.321
And I did my Law Degree at Yale

00:04:06.321 --> 00:04:09.140
where, we don't have majors in law school

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:11.970
but I worked primarily in
the fields I still do now,

00:04:11.970 --> 00:04:14.700
constitutional law and
international affairs.

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:18.620
- And when where you
bitten by bug to look at

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:20.700
foreign policy, international law,

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:22.310
the power of the president,

00:04:22.310 --> 00:04:24.410
those set of things that
run throughout your work?

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:27.810
- Actually it comes all
the way from middle school.

00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:30.190
Well part of it is just,

00:04:30.190 --> 00:04:32.500
having come from Korea,
being an immigrant,

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.139
and coming from a place where
the United States fought,

00:04:35.139 --> 00:04:39.320
and drew in one of its Cold War battles.

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:41.168
So that story of course, would make me

00:04:41.168 --> 00:04:43.244
sort of interested in the beginning.

00:04:43.244 --> 00:04:46.983
The second thing is I went to a school,

00:04:46.983 --> 00:04:48.640
in middle school and high school

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:51.100
that heavily emphasized
Western civilization

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:53.505
and the study of the classics.

00:04:53.505 --> 00:04:58.505
So I read a lot about Greek and
Roman sources and histories,

00:04:58.718 --> 00:05:02.000
which are, a lot of it is about

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.713
what we would think of today
as foreign affairs, politics,

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:09.740
military and so on.

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:12.390
And so I was interested even
before I got to college,

00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:15.034
and then when I got to
college I got to study

00:05:15.034 --> 00:05:18.819
a lot different aspects
of international relations

00:05:18.819 --> 00:05:23.819
as it interacted with the
American domestic system.

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:26.425
And then, law school, certainly

00:05:26.425 --> 00:05:28.720
more finely narrowed that down

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:32.033
to really the legal aspects of that.

00:05:32.033 --> 00:05:34.620
- And did you have any professors either

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.270
as an undergraduate or at law school

00:05:37.270 --> 00:05:39.360
who heavily influenced you?

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:42.516
- Yes, in college I was

00:05:42.516 --> 00:05:46.510
heavily influenced by two professors who,

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:48.910
and it's probably the
normal course at Harvard,

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:51.673
neither of them are there anymore and,

00:05:52.669 --> 00:05:55.421
one was Thomas Schwartz,
who's a professor of history,

00:05:55.421 --> 00:05:59.700
at Vanderbilt who was a real student

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:02.677
of the German reconstruction
period after World War II

00:06:02.677 --> 00:06:04.370
and is just last, I think two years ago

00:06:04.370 --> 00:06:06.835
came out with this book about
Lyndon Johnson in Europe.

00:06:06.835 --> 00:06:09.470
The other professor I was
close to was Brian Ballou

00:06:09.470 --> 00:06:11.500
who's a professor of history at Virginia

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:14.121
and he was a student of the
American administrative state.

00:06:14.121 --> 00:06:17.330
So actually if you think
about those two interests

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:20.723
that actually combined
from those two areas.

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:25.070
And law school, I was or
the people I was closest to,

00:06:25.070 --> 00:06:28.560
Peter Schuck, who's been
many times to UC Berkeley,

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:30.000
probably be back again,

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:31.450
student of administrative law,

00:06:31.450 --> 00:06:34.060
Harrold Kohs, say foreign
affairs and Akila Marr

00:06:34.060 --> 00:06:36.113
who really studied constitution from

00:06:36.113 --> 00:06:38.635
an originalist perspective and so again,

00:06:38.635 --> 00:06:40.803
all three of those are,

00:06:41.653 --> 00:06:44.140
continue to be influences
on my work today.

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:47.030
- How were you affected
by the Reagan revolution,

00:06:47.030 --> 00:06:47.921
or were you?

00:06:47.921 --> 00:06:52.921
- You know, given the kind of
millue I think I came out of

00:06:53.876 --> 00:06:58.650
I was very supportive of
President Reagan's policies,

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:00.390
particularly in foreign affairs.

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:04.280
The idea that the Soviet
Union was an evil empire,

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:07.380
it was an evil system
and the United States

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:09.470
was appropriately trying to defeat it,

00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:12.160
not just reach some state
of coexistence with it,

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:16.050
but to actually win in the Cold
War is very attractive to me

00:07:16.050 --> 00:07:19.590
and he, Carter was really the president

00:07:19.590 --> 00:07:21.939
I was really conscious of.

00:07:21.939 --> 00:07:24.320
There's a sharp difference between the two

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:29.320
and I really though Reagan had
foreign policy about right.

00:07:29.718 --> 00:07:32.195
Domestic policy, I sort of like the idea

00:07:32.195 --> 00:07:33.747
of lower tax cuts.

00:07:33.747 --> 00:07:36.150
I mean more tax cuts, lower government

00:07:36.150 --> 00:07:38.047
intervention in society.

00:07:38.047 --> 00:07:42.440
More space for private activity.

00:07:42.440 --> 00:07:44.710
People sometimes find it odd that I'm a

00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:47.285
libertarian when it comes
to domestic social issues

00:07:47.285 --> 00:07:49.813
as opposed to foreign affairs.

00:07:51.275 --> 00:07:54.210
However, Reagan did not cut spending,

00:07:54.210 --> 00:07:55.960
which he should have done.

00:07:55.960 --> 00:07:58.710
But other than that, the
other aspects of his policy

00:07:58.710 --> 00:08:03.290
I thought were, I very much agreed with.

00:08:03.290 --> 00:08:05.380
- In one of the books or
one of the articles I read,

00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:08.190
it mentioned that you,
the federalist society,

00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:12.850
that you joined that when
there were only eight members

00:08:12.850 --> 00:08:16.220
and it was made up of
conservatives and libertarians,

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:17.240
I think it said.

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:21.625
So there is this dycotomy
in the conservative,

00:08:21.625 --> 00:08:24.560
in what we came to think of
as the conservative movement

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:25.960
and also in your own thinking.

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:28.910
- Oh yeah, there is, I
mean people maybe generally

00:08:28.910 --> 00:08:31.170
don't realize it but
within what's thought of

00:08:31.170 --> 00:08:34.060
as the conservative legal movement,

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:36.625
there's a deep division
between libertarians

00:08:36.625 --> 00:08:40.020
who are just relatively suspicious

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:42.420
of government power on any form.

00:08:42.420 --> 00:08:44.206
No matter what level of government it is.

00:08:44.206 --> 00:08:48.296
And I would think of as
more social conservatives

00:08:48.296 --> 00:08:51.749
or big government
conservatives, which also

00:08:51.749 --> 00:08:55.297
runs through the Republican Party too.

00:08:55.297 --> 00:08:57.090
And there's no resolution of it.

00:08:57.090 --> 00:08:59.801
And one thing the federal
society is good about

00:08:59.801 --> 00:09:03.380
is that it provides a forum to those two

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:04.771
groups to debate things.

00:09:04.771 --> 00:09:07.010
One great issue that they debate about

00:09:07.010 --> 00:09:09.870
and disagree about is
wire tapping, for example.

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:13.252
The war on terrorism,
so there's not unified

00:09:13.252 --> 00:09:16.025
view amongst legal conservatives.

00:09:16.025 --> 00:09:18.870
- During this formative
experience there was

00:09:18.870 --> 00:09:21.418
a lot of energy in the
conservative movement.

00:09:21.418 --> 00:09:24.907
It was an exciting time
to become a conservative.

00:09:24.907 --> 00:09:26.811
That's fair, isn't it?

00:09:26.811 --> 00:09:29.740
- Yeah, I mean I think, it's interesting.

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:33.260
The dominant sort of,

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:35.180
the dominant way of thought at that time

00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:38.100
was still, I think fairly
liberal and so if you

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:40.440
were a conservative,
particularly the place

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:42.263
like Harvard or Yale
or any major university

00:09:42.263 --> 00:09:45.320
at that time, conservatives
were sort of more

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:47.560
the radicals, I guess they were.

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:49.635
They were trying to overturn the way

00:09:49.635 --> 00:09:51.741
things had been going for some time.

00:09:51.741 --> 00:09:53.936
So yeah it was more exciting.

00:09:53.936 --> 00:09:55.819
The people involved were maybe younger.

00:09:55.819 --> 00:09:58.470
They had the fresher and newer ideas.

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:00.230
They were more fun to debate about them,

00:10:00.230 --> 00:10:04.590
whereas what I think of
as a liberal orthodox

00:10:04.590 --> 00:10:08.260
either had really been a
product of the new deal.

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:10.868
And then Roosevelt and Johnson and Carter

00:10:10.868 --> 00:10:13.250
seemed tired and defensive.

00:10:13.250 --> 00:10:14.265
- Mh-mmm.

00:10:14.265 --> 00:10:16.970
You've been fortunate to have a number

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:21.970
of legal mentors, Judge Silverman first.

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:24.770
Then Justice Thomas.

00:10:24.770 --> 00:10:27.040
And then you also worked for Orin Hetch.

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:29.660
Talk a little about each of them briefly

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:32.090
and how they influenced
you because they really

00:10:32.090 --> 00:10:34.593
gave you a view of
national security issues,

00:10:34.593 --> 00:10:37.470
conservative legal scholarship,

00:10:37.470 --> 00:10:42.228
and then finally the
view from the congress.

00:10:42.228 --> 00:10:45.572
- I learned a great deal
from all three of them.

00:10:45.572 --> 00:10:50.572
They've all been very
influential mentors of mine.

00:10:51.590 --> 00:10:55.270
Judge Silverman is the first
person I had a real job under.

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:57.290
You serve as a law
clerk which means you're

00:10:57.290 --> 00:11:00.219
their assistant, you help
the judge research cases.

00:11:00.219 --> 00:11:03.280
If they want you to find what the laws

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:04.890
of some subject you go find it.

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:07.190
You help them prepare for oral arguments.

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:08.437
You basically,

00:11:08.437 --> 00:11:11.670
research assistant, basically.

00:11:11.670 --> 00:11:13.980
In a way, professors have them.

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:17.186
And he was a really good for me because he

00:11:17.186 --> 00:11:19.990
was someone who combined those
things I was interested in.

00:11:19.990 --> 00:11:22.074
He had been an ambassador.

00:11:22.074 --> 00:11:24.201
He was ambassador to Ugoslavia.

00:11:24.201 --> 00:11:28.870
And he's continued to be a
figure in foreign affairs

00:11:28.870 --> 00:11:30.852
and national security even
though he's a judge and a lawyer.

00:11:30.852 --> 00:11:35.219
He's not a pure policy person.

00:11:35.219 --> 00:11:37.700
But someone who trained in law.

00:11:37.700 --> 00:11:40.187
So even just a few years
ago he was the joint

00:11:40.187 --> 00:11:43.050
chairman on the president's commission

00:11:43.050 --> 00:11:46.237
on the WMD in Iraq study.

00:11:46.237 --> 00:11:47.900
So he continues to play a role.

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:50.090
So that was very,

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:51.940
that was very important to me to see that

00:11:51.940 --> 00:11:54.340
the things I was interested
in could lead to a career.

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:56.530
And to see how he thought things through.

00:11:56.530 --> 00:11:58.472
He was the first real lawyer I worked for.

00:11:58.472 --> 00:12:03.472
Justice Thomas is also very

00:12:03.690 --> 00:12:05.781
influential person in the way I thought,

00:12:05.781 --> 00:12:07.730
or the way I think.

00:12:07.730 --> 00:12:10.160
He taught me a number of things.

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:13.490
One thing he taught me was not to really

00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:15.109
worry so much about criticism.

00:12:15.109 --> 00:12:19.810
He really thinks the key thing in any

00:12:19.810 --> 00:12:22.840
of these things we do is
to reach what you think

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:24.150
is the right answer.

00:12:24.150 --> 00:12:25.400
And if you think it's the right answer,

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:26.497
then defend it.

00:12:26.497 --> 00:12:30.600
And not to be so swayed by criticism.

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:32.250
Not that you don't pay attention to what

00:12:32.250 --> 00:12:33.710
other people's arguments and views are,

00:12:33.710 --> 00:12:36.110
but you consider them
all and then you make

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:37.810
your decision and then you live with it.

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:41.000
You don't sway back and
forth based on criticism.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.510
And so he's been criticized a lot.

00:12:43.510 --> 00:12:45.763
He's one of the most
criticized public figures.

00:12:45.763 --> 00:12:49.144
And I think what I saw
was a person who continued

00:12:49.144 --> 00:12:51.550
to do his job and continued to stand up

00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:52.712
for what he believed in.

00:12:52.712 --> 00:12:57.250
Senator Hatch, again I
was very lucky, again

00:12:57.250 --> 00:12:58.723
to work for a wonderful guy

00:12:58.723 --> 00:13:02.160
and someone who taught me
about how politics works.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:04.660
So what I've always often
said to students is that

00:13:06.091 --> 00:13:07.870
we can prepare you in law school how

00:13:07.870 --> 00:13:09.118
to be a judicial clerk.

00:13:09.118 --> 00:13:11.110
I think you can be prepared in law school

00:13:11.110 --> 00:13:13.251
or graduate school how to
work in the executive branch.

00:13:13.251 --> 00:13:17.400
And I don't think in, no
offense to political scientistt

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:19.130
or to lawyers, I don't
think we have a clue

00:13:19.130 --> 00:13:21.076
how to teach people how
to work in congress.

00:13:21.076 --> 00:13:24.553
You can't have a class on congress 101

00:13:24.553 --> 00:13:26.690
that really tells you what a lobbyist does

00:13:26.690 --> 00:13:27.800
and how you would do it.

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:28.840
How you would be a staffer.

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:30.570
How you work things through the political

00:13:30.570 --> 00:13:32.257
process in congress.

00:13:32.257 --> 00:13:34.163
What are hearings really like?

00:13:34.163 --> 00:13:35.547
How do you run?

00:13:35.547 --> 00:13:38.090
So of all the jobs I've actually had

00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:40.400
I think I learned the
most from Senator Hatch

00:13:40.400 --> 00:13:41.660
in that one year I worked for him

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:44.080
because there's no way right now we can

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:47.083
effectively teach that
experience in the classroom.

00:13:48.180 --> 00:13:49.657
- Which leads me to my next question.

00:13:49.657 --> 00:13:54.151
What do you think it takes
to do the kind of law

00:13:54.151 --> 00:13:56.840
that you do, it's not tort law.

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:58.120
It's not contracts.

00:13:58.120 --> 00:14:03.120
It's really sort of the
constitution international

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:05.000
relations, it's a very

00:14:08.429 --> 00:14:12.280
hard thing to get your hands on, my view.

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:14.470
- In the law school what they would say,

00:14:14.470 --> 00:14:16.773
it's a hard thing to bill hours for.

00:14:16.773 --> 00:14:18.374
In the sense that
- You don't work

00:14:18.374 --> 00:14:20.370
for government.
- You obviously make money.

00:14:20.370 --> 00:14:22.320
There's no law firms that have a practice

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:23.658
in foreign affairs law.

00:14:23.658 --> 00:14:24.980
- That's it.

00:14:24.980 --> 00:14:27.013
So what does it take to do that?

00:14:27.013 --> 00:14:28.960
Idealism, I guess?

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:31.250
- Well first of all, I think you're not

00:14:31.250 --> 00:14:32.640
gonna make a lot of money if you go

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:35.420
into that kind of work
and most of the work

00:14:35.420 --> 00:14:36.543
is in the government.

00:14:38.423 --> 00:14:40.880
You get into corporate,
to extent, companies

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:41.840
might get involved in it.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:43.970
It's really to extent their
multinational companies

00:14:43.970 --> 00:14:46.341
and they run across issues,
but really the things

00:14:46.341 --> 00:14:49.285
I'm concerned about war powers,
treaty powers and so on,

00:14:49.285 --> 00:14:52.658
don't really rise that
much in private practice.

00:14:52.658 --> 00:14:55.390
So the only real way
to get experience in it

00:14:55.390 --> 00:14:58.186
and to learn about it is by doing it.

00:14:58.186 --> 00:15:00.871
So I've had the opportunity to work

00:15:00.871 --> 00:15:02.913
in all three branches of the government

00:15:02.913 --> 00:15:04.480
and to see these kinds of issues

00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:06.580
from each of those different perspectives.

00:15:07.616 --> 00:15:09.750
And there's a lot of jobs, not a lot,

