on I suppose your
question can be translated

00:53:04.990 --> 00:53:07.130
into this idea, well
you did not anticipate

00:53:07.130 --> 00:53:08.901
how high the errors would be.

00:53:08.901 --> 00:53:12.260
And you would have to think about,

00:53:12.260 --> 00:53:14.700
well what would the system
to correct those errors

00:53:14.700 --> 00:53:16.684
look like and how much would it cost.

00:53:16.684 --> 00:53:20.830
And what's the benefit of
following the rules you set out.

00:53:20.830 --> 00:53:24.527
We have errors, we have
errors in beauracratic systems

00:53:24.527 --> 00:53:28.570
in the United States, in
the university all the time.

00:53:28.570 --> 00:53:30.520
But there are costs we live with in order

00:53:30.520 --> 00:53:32.000
to get the benefits or whatever it is.

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:34.557
So those are all variables I think of.

00:53:34.557 --> 00:53:36.808
I have to say in the
writing on these issues,

00:53:36.808 --> 00:53:40.942
that really isn't something
the memos were about

00:53:40.942 --> 00:53:42.395
or designed to do.

00:53:42.395 --> 00:53:45.480
And in some ways as a lawyer,

00:53:45.480 --> 00:53:46.940
would not have been my job.

00:53:46.940 --> 00:53:49.110
I would've been going
too far if I had said,

00:53:49.110 --> 00:53:50.800
here I'm interpreting this law,

00:53:50.800 --> 00:53:52.510
but here are these other things
you better be worried about.

00:53:52.510 --> 00:53:54.770
It wouldn't be part of
the job of that office.

00:53:54.770 --> 00:53:57.717
It might be advice one could give,

00:53:57.717 --> 00:54:00.930
but doesn't have anything to do with a law

00:54:00.930 --> 00:54:02.710
and my view wouldn't
be entitled to any kind

00:54:02.710 --> 00:54:06.310
of special value as opposed to anyone else

00:54:06.310 --> 00:54:07.650
in the governments on those issues.

00:54:07.650 --> 00:54:09.766
In fact, I might be someone
who's less qualified

00:54:09.766 --> 00:54:13.232
to advise someone about that
because my specialization

00:54:13.232 --> 00:54:16.390
is just interpreting law
here and not figuring out

00:54:16.390 --> 00:54:18.374
how do you actually now
make it work in practice.

00:54:18.374 --> 00:54:23.374
- You wrote in this book,
the War by Other Means,

00:54:24.500 --> 00:54:29.070
which I guess I should show,
I never showed our audience,

00:54:29.070 --> 00:54:30.700
which is an account of your experience.

00:54:30.700 --> 00:54:31.890
You wrote I think in the--

00:54:31.890 --> 00:54:33.710
- My publishers, though they're different,

00:54:33.710 --> 00:54:36.040
they all like to stick
stars on the book covers.

00:54:36.040 --> 00:54:37.580
- I see, yeah.

00:54:37.580 --> 00:54:41.730
You wrote upon confrontation and questions

00:54:41.730 --> 00:54:44.117
of its policies, the Bush Administration

00:54:44.117 --> 00:54:47.000
tended to run and hide.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:50.373
I have a sense that you say,
okay this is what I think.

00:54:50.373 --> 00:54:53.350
My scholarship tells me this.

00:54:53.350 --> 00:54:55.493
My political inclinations.

00:54:55.493 --> 00:54:58.879
And you would incline
more toward the airing

00:54:58.879 --> 00:55:01.685
of these things so
there should be a debate

00:55:01.685 --> 00:55:04.510
and that the political process would then

00:55:04.510 --> 00:55:08.230
maybe retreat from what you
thought was the best, yeah.

00:55:08.230 --> 00:55:09.315
- I agree.

00:55:09.315 --> 00:55:11.410
I think the one problem,

00:55:11.410 --> 00:55:14.220
a big problem in a lot of these
wars on terrors and issues

00:55:14.220 --> 00:55:18.950
is it's not just that
initially there wasn't debate,

00:55:18.950 --> 00:55:21.836
but then after a period
of time you could have

00:55:21.836 --> 00:55:24.459
debate, obviously, and I
think the administration

00:55:24.459 --> 00:55:26.724
ceded the field to its critics.

00:55:26.724 --> 00:55:29.228
I think the administration
has very good reasons

00:55:29.228 --> 00:55:32.590
for a lot of the policies
that we should, it wasn't,

00:55:32.590 --> 00:55:35.340
but if you read the press
and follow it publicly,

00:55:35.340 --> 00:55:36.270
you would think that these were the most

00:55:36.270 --> 00:55:39.460
irrational arbitrary decisions just made

00:55:39.460 --> 00:55:41.533
to agrandize the power of the president

00:55:41.533 --> 00:55:45.220
or the vice president and I don't think

00:55:45.220 --> 00:55:46.053
that's the case at all.

00:55:46.053 --> 00:55:47.660
I think these are,

00:55:47.660 --> 00:55:49.810
and I think it's an illusion
to think they're easy.

00:55:49.810 --> 00:55:51.721
I think these are very hard questions

00:55:51.721 --> 00:55:54.121
and there are costs and benefits to every

00:55:54.121 --> 00:55:55.593
decision you make.

00:55:57.430 --> 00:55:58.790
And I think the
administration just doesn't

00:55:58.790 --> 00:56:00.560
explain itself very well or chose,

00:56:00.560 --> 00:56:03.133
I think with the, when
the Geneva Conventions

00:56:03.133 --> 00:56:05.289
and interrogation issue,
chose not to explain at all.

00:56:05.289 --> 00:56:08.747
And I think only when it
came down to the wire tapping

00:56:08.747 --> 00:56:12.440
cases did the administration
really start coming out

00:56:12.440 --> 00:56:14.250
and explaining why it did what it did,

00:56:14.250 --> 00:56:15.883
why it thought it could do that.

00:56:15.883 --> 00:56:18.564
And then we also started learning later

00:56:18.564 --> 00:56:21.950
that the executive branch was actually

00:56:21.950 --> 00:56:23.900
secretly briefing and
consulting with members

00:56:23.900 --> 00:56:25.890
of congress about all of these things

00:56:25.890 --> 00:56:28.066
to try to get some kind of...

00:56:28.066 --> 00:56:30.250
In response to one of
your previous questions,

00:56:30.250 --> 00:56:32.650
how do you deal with this,
you have war time pressures

00:56:32.650 --> 00:56:34.580
but have a government that's supposed to

00:56:34.580 --> 00:56:37.060
openly disclose policy choices.

00:56:37.060 --> 00:56:38.920
What the administration
clearly tried to do

00:56:38.920 --> 00:56:41.790
was to not have the
information become public

00:56:41.790 --> 00:56:43.940
so it would help the
enemy, but at the same time

00:56:43.940 --> 00:56:47.260
try to have some kind of sort of

00:56:47.260 --> 00:56:49.770
political consultation by secretly talking

00:56:49.770 --> 00:56:51.388
to leaders of congress.

00:56:51.388 --> 00:56:54.666
But I agree, that doesn't
substitute for a full

00:56:54.666 --> 00:56:57.460
bore robust public discussion,

00:56:57.460 --> 00:56:59.580
and I don't understand
why you wouldn't have it

00:56:59.580 --> 00:57:01.010
once it's already become public.

00:57:01.010 --> 00:57:02.944
But that's what they did and I think it's,

00:57:02.944 --> 00:57:04.610
I think that's a big problem

00:57:04.610 --> 00:57:07.160
and sort of a self inflicted wound

00:57:07.160 --> 00:57:09.500
that the administration has suffered.

00:57:09.500 --> 00:57:11.587
- One final question
requiring a brief answer

00:57:11.587 --> 00:57:13.780
because we're running out
of time, but you know,

00:57:13.780 --> 00:57:16.548
my sense of American
politics is the pendulum

00:57:16.548 --> 00:57:19.911
swings back the other way over time.

00:57:19.911 --> 00:57:22.519
Liberal, conservative, whatever.

00:57:22.519 --> 00:57:25.370
Do you see that happening
here and what will

00:57:25.370 --> 00:57:29.190
be the consequences for both the country

00:57:29.190 --> 00:57:30.540
and actually for the people who were

00:57:30.540 --> 00:57:31.633
involved in these decisions?

00:57:31.633 --> 00:57:33.240
- Yeah so very interesting question.

00:57:33.240 --> 00:57:38.150
I think after Vietnam you say
and the Nixon Administration,

00:57:38.150 --> 00:57:40.313
you saw weakening of executive power.

00:57:40.313 --> 00:57:42.710
The thing that's, I think, fairly striking

00:57:42.710 --> 00:57:45.682
is that it actually lasted
fairly short period of time.

00:57:45.682 --> 00:57:48.900
It lasted the rest of
Nixon's Administration

00:57:48.900 --> 00:57:50.564
which under President Ford and then the

00:57:50.564 --> 00:57:52.595
Carter Administration, one term.

00:57:52.595 --> 00:57:55.240
And then by the Reagan
Administration you had

00:57:55.240 --> 00:57:56.610
a lot of people in the political system

00:57:56.610 --> 00:57:59.293
wanting a return to a vigorous executive.

00:57:59.293 --> 00:58:03.700
So it's certainly possible
that the dissatisfaction

00:58:03.700 --> 00:58:06.110
with the war, although
I think it's primarily

00:58:06.110 --> 00:58:08.750
the war in Iraq and not
the war on terrorism

00:58:08.750 --> 00:58:11.219
that's causing the great dissatisfaction,

00:58:11.219 --> 00:58:15.020
will produce a shift away
from executive power.

00:58:15.020 --> 00:58:18.290
But I think it's gonna
return, not because I happen

00:58:18.290 --> 00:58:21.360
to favor it that way
or I think it's because

00:58:21.360 --> 00:58:23.351
of complexity of the world
and foreign challenges,

00:58:23.351 --> 00:58:26.866
and the threat of
terrorism's not going away.

00:58:26.866 --> 00:58:29.530
And we're not gonna have
a congress manage that

00:58:29.530 --> 00:58:31.310
day to day in the details.

00:58:31.310 --> 00:58:33.530
It's still gonna be the job,
and always gonna be the job,

00:58:33.530 --> 00:58:35.040
of the executive branch.

00:58:35.040 --> 00:58:38.520
